<h2>Bird-of-Paradise</h2>

<img src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/6/6e/Paradisaea_raggiana_-_Raggiana_Bird-of-paradise.jpg"
alt="Raggiana Bird-of-Paradise">

<p>
The <strong>Bird-of-Paradise</strong> is the national emblem of Papua New Guinea (PNG).
The species represented is the <strong>Raggiana Bird-of-Paradise (Paradisaea raggiana)</strong>.
It is one of the world's most beautiful birds and is famous for its brilliant red-orange
plumes, yellow head, emerald-green throat, and spectacular courtship dance.
</p>

<h2>Description</h2>

<p>
The Bird-of-Paradise belongs to the family Paradisaeidae and lives mainly in the tropical
rainforests of Papua New Guinea. Males are brightly coloured and have long ornamental
tail feathers, while females are smaller and brown in colour for camouflage.
</p>

<h2>Habitat</h2>

<ul>
<li>Tropical rainforests</li>
<li>Forest edges</li>
<li>Mountain forests</li>
<li>Lowland forests</li>
</ul>

<h2>Diet</h2>

<ul>
<li>Fruits</li>
<li>Berries</li>
<li>Seeds</li>
<li>Insects</li>
<li>Small invertebrates</li>
</ul>

<h2>Characteristics</h2>

<ul>
<li>Scientific Name: <em>Paradisaea raggiana</em></li>
<li>Family: Paradisaeidae</li>
<li>Average Length: 34 cm</li>
<li>Lifespan: 8–15 years in the wild</li>
<li>Colour: Red-orange plumes, yellow head, green throat</li>
<li>Behaviour: Famous for elaborate courtship dances</li>
</ul>

<h2>Importance to Papua New Guinea</h2>

<p>
The Bird-of-Paradise symbolizes freedom, beauty, pride, cultural diversity, and the rich
natural heritage of Papua New Guinea. It appears on the National Coat of Arms together
with a ceremonial spear and a Kundu drum, representing the traditions and unity of the
people of PNG. The bird also appears on the national flag, government emblems, and many
official documents.
</p>

<h2>Interesting Facts</h2>

<ul>
<li>There are over 40 species of Birds-of-Paradise.</li>
<li>Papua New Guinea is home to most of these species.</li>
<li>The male performs elaborate dances to attract females.</li>
<li>The Raggiana Bird-of-Paradise has been the national emblem since Papua New Guinea gained independence in 1975.</li>
</ul>

